HEADWORD: Henchman
<hw>Hench"man</hw> <pr>(h⟦ecr⟧nch"m⟦ait⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>-men</plw> <pr>(-m⟦eit⟧n)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE.
<ets>hencheman</ets>, <ets>henxman</ets>; prob. fr. OE. & AS.
<ets>hengest</ets> horse + E. <ets>man</ets>, and meaning, a groom. AS.
<ets>hengest</ets> is akin to D. & G. <ets>hengst</ets> stallion, OHG.
<ets>hengist</ets> horse, gelding.]</ety> <def>An attendant; a servant;
a follower. Now chiefly used as a political cant term.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

